Humans, a species whose self-assigned moniker, *[Homo sapiens](/Homo_sapiens)* — 'wise man' or 'knowledgeable man' — often feels like an optimistic overstatement, are, at their core, [primates](/Primates). We belong to the rather dramatic [biological family](/Family_(biology)) of [great apes](/Great_ape), distinguished by a peculiar combination of traits that, when viewed through a cosmic lens, are both remarkable and utterly predictable. Among these defining characteristics are our relative [hairlessness](/Prehistory_of_nakedness_and_clothing) (a curious evolutionary choice, really), our consistent [bipedality](/Bipedality) – the upright strut that seems to demand attention – and, of course, our notoriously high, if not always well-utilized, [intelligence](/Human_intelligence).

Our oversized [brains](/Human_brain), disproportionately large [compared to body size](/Brain-body_mass_ratio), have indeed gifted us with advanced [cognitive](/Cognitive) skills. These aren't just for contemplating the void; they've facilitated our rather successful, if often destructive, adaptation to nearly every conceivable environment. They've driven the development of increasingly sophisticated [tools](/Tool) – from chipped stone to digital interfaces – and enabled the construction of fantastically intricate [social structures](/Social_structures) and sprawling [civilizations](/Civilization). Whether these structures are truly *better* is, of course, a matter for endless, tiresome debate.

Humans are, to put it mildly, [highly social](/Sociality) creatures. Individuals inevitably find themselves entangled in [multi-layered](/Level_of_analysis) networks of distinct [social groups](/Social_groups). These range from the intimate, often chaotic confines of [families](/Families) and fleeting [peer groups](/Peer_groups) to the vast, impersonal machinations of [corporations](/Corporations) and the often-dysfunctional apparatus of [political states](/State_(polity)). These incessant [social interactions](/Social_interaction) have, over millennia, forged an astonishingly diverse tapestry of [values](/Value_theory), unwritten [social norms](/Norm_(sociology)), complex [languages](/Language), and deeply ingrained [traditions](/Traditions), all bundled together under the rather abstract term of [institutions](/Institutions). Each of these, in its own way, acts as a scaffold, bolstering the precarious edifice of [human society](/Society).

Beyond mere survival and social maneuvering, humans exhibit a profound, almost pathological, [curiosity](/Curious). This relentless desire to comprehend – and, more often than not, to manipulate – [phenomena](/Phenomenon) has been the engine behind humanity's relentless pursuit of [science](/Science), the ceaseless innovation of [technology](/Technology), the abstract meanderings of [philosophy](/Philosophy), the comforting narratives of [mythology](/Mythology), and the often-conflicting tenets of [religion](/Religion). These, along with countless other frameworks of [knowledge](/Knowledge), represent our attempts to make sense of a universe that frankly doesn't care. Ironically, we also turn this intense scrutiny upon ourselves, through fields such as [anthropology](/Anthropology), [social science](/Social_science), [history](/History), [psychology](/Psychology), and [medicine](/Medicine) – as if self-analysis might actually yield a definitive answer to "what are we?" As of 2025, the sheer volume of this self-studying, self-replicating species is staggering: there are estimated to be [more than 8 billion living humans](/World_population) crowding this small planet. A truly impressive, if somewhat concerning, number.

Historically, for the vast majority of our existence, humans were [nomadic](/Nomadic) [hunter-gatherers](/Hunter-gatherer), a lifestyle that, one might argue, was far more ecologically sound. The shift to what we optimistically call "[behavioral modernity](/Behavioral_modality)" began to manifest roughly 160,000 to 60,000 years ago. Then came the [Neolithic Revolution](/Neolithic_Revolution), a series of independent developments in multiple regions, kick-starting approximately 13,000 years ago [in Southwest Asia](/Origins_of_agriculture_in_West_Asia). This era marked the advent of [agriculture](/Agriculture) and the unsettling permanence of [human settlement](/Human_settlement). This, in turn, inevitably led to the [development of civilization](/Cradle_of_civilization) – a process that ushered in an unbroken, and indeed still accelerating, period of [population growth](/Population_growth) and astonishingly rapid [technological change](/Technological_change). Since that pivotal shift, countless [civilizations](/Civilization) have risen, flourished, and, with predictable regularity, crumbled into dust, each cycle marked by continuous [sociocultural](/Sociocultural_evolution) and [technological](/History_of_technology) advancements that have fundamentally, and often irrevocably, reshaped the human lifestyle.

Humans are, by dietary necessity, [omnivorous](/Omnivorous), capable of processing a truly vast array of plant and animal matter. We have, with remarkable ingenuity, [used fire](/Control_of_fire_by_early_humans) and other forms of heat to prepare and [cook](/Cooking) our food since the time of [Homo erectus](/Homo_erectus), a practice that undoubtedly broadened our dietary horizons. Generally, we are [diurnal](/Diurnality) creatures, typically demanding a solid seven to nine hours of [sleep](/Sleep) per day – a requirement often ignored by modern society, much to its detriment. Our species has exerted a dramatic, some might say catastrophic, [effect on the environment](/Human_impact_on_the_environment). We are, by virtually any measure, [apex predators](/Apex_predator), rarely finding ourselves in the unenviable position of being prey for other species. However, our relentless [population growth](/Population_growth), coupled with unchecked [industrialisation](/Industrialisation), expansive [land development](/Land_development), rampant [overconsumption](/Overconsumption), and the ceaseless combustion of [fossil fuels](/Fossil_fuels), has plunged the planet into an era of profound [environmental destruction](/Environmental_destruction) and pervasive [pollution](/Pollution). This self-inflicted ecological wound is a significant, undeniable contributor to the ongoing [mass extinction](/Holocene_extinction) of countless other forms of life. Within the last century, our insatiable drive has pushed us to explore the most challenging environments imaginable: the desolate expanse of [Antarctica](/Antarctica), the crushing depths of the [deep sea](/Deep_sea), and the silent, indifferent void of [outer space](/Outer_space). While human habitation in these extreme locales is usually fleeting and confined to [scientific](/Scientific), [military](/Military), or [industrial](/Industry_(economics)) expeditions, we have, with a mix of audacity and perhaps a touch of desperation, even visited the [Moon](/Moon) and launched human-made [spacecraft](/Spacecraft) to other distant [celestial bodies](/Celestial_bodies), thereby becoming the first known species to reach beyond its planetary cradle.

Although the scientific term "humans" technically encompasses all members, living and extinct, of the [genus](/Genus) [Homo](/Homo), in common, less precise usage, it almost exclusively refers to *[Homo sapiens](/Homo_sapiens)*, our own species, which is, rather conveniently, the only [extant](/Extant_taxon) member. All other members of the genus *Homo*, now tragically extinct, are relegated to the category of "[archaic humans](/Archaic_humans)," while the qualifier "modern human" is often employed to draw a distinction between *Homo sapiens* and these earlier, less fortunate hominins. [Anatomically modern humans](/Early_modern_human) first graced the stage at least 300,000 years ago in [Africa](/Africa), evolving from [Homo heidelbergensis](/Homo_heidelbergensis) or a closely related species. From this African crucible, they embarked on a series of migrations [out of Africa](/Recent_African_origin_of_modern_humans), gradually, and often ruthlessly, replacing, or indeed [interbreeding](/Hybrid_(biology)) with, the local populations of archaic humans they encountered. Multiple hypotheses swirl around the extinction of these archaic human species, [such as Neanderthals](/Neanderthal_extinction), ranging from direct competition and outright violence to genetic dilution through interbreeding with *Homo sapiens*, or simply a tragic inability to adapt to shifting [climate change](/Climate_variability_and_change). Our [human biology](/Human_biology) displays variation in a multitude of visible characteristics, [physiology](/Physiology), susceptibility to disease, mental abilities, body size, and [life span](/Life_expectancy), all influenced by the intricate dance between our [genes](/Gene) and the [environment](/Environment_(biophysical)). Despite this apparent diversity, humans are, genetically speaking, among the least diverse [primates](/Primates). Any two individuals, picked at random, will share at least 99% of their genetic code – a testament to our relatively recent common ancestry.

Humans exhibit clear [sexual dimorphism](/Sex_differences_in_humans): typically, [males](/Man) possess greater overall body strength, while [females](/Woman) generally carry a higher percentage of [body fat](/Body_fat). At the onset of [puberty](/Puberty), both sexes develop distinct [secondary sex characteristics](/Secondary_sex_characteristic). Females are capable of [pregnancy](/Pregnancy), a biological window that generally spans from puberty, usually around 12 years of age, until [menopause](/Menopause), which typically occurs around 50. [Childbirth](/Childbirth) is, by any objective measure, a perilous undertaking, fraught with a high risk of complications and even [death](/Death) – a biological design flaw, if you ask me. Interestingly, in human societies, both the mother and the father often share the burden of caring for their offspring, who are notoriously [helpless at birth](/Precociality_and_altriciality) and require prolonged nurturing.

### Etymology and definition

One might wonder how this peculiar species came to be labeled. The renowned taxonomist [Carl Linnaeus](/Carl_Linnaeus), in his 1735 magnum opus, *[Systema Naturae](/Systema_Naturae)*, bestowed upon us the rather grandiose name *[Homo sapiens](/Homo_sapiens)*. This generic name, [Homo](/Homo), is a learned 18th-century derivation from the Latin *homō*, a term that, rather inclusively, referred to humans of either sex. And, as a matter of pedantic clarification, the word "human" *can* indeed refer to all members of the entire *Homo* genus, not just our self-congratulatory species. The name *Homo sapiens* itself translates, with a touch of hubris, to 'wise man' or 'knowledgeable man'. There remains a perpetual, and somewhat tiresome, [disagreement](/Species) among specialists as to whether certain extinct members of the genus, notably the [Neanderthals](/Neanderthal), should be classified as a distinct species of "humans" or merely as a [subspecies](/Subspecies) of *H. sapiens*. It's a debate that, frankly, reveals more about human squabbles over categorization than it does about the Neanderthals themselves.

The term "human" is a [loanword](/Loanword) that infiltrated [Middle English](/Middle_English) from the [Old French](/Old_French) "humain," which itself ultimately stemmed from the Latin *hūmānus*. This Latin root was the adjectival form of *homō*, meaning 'man' in the broader sense of humanity. Interestingly, the native English term "[man](/Man_(word))" also carried this dual meaning, referring to the species generally (as a synonym for "humanity") as well as, more specifically, to human males. It could, in older usage, even refer to individuals of either sex, adding another layer of linguistic ambiguity to our self-referential terms.

Despite the common, and frankly irritating, colloquial habit of using "animal" as an antonym for "human," a practice that flies in the face of basic biological understanding, and contrary to a prevalent [biological misconception](/List_of_common_misconceptions_about_science,_technology,_and_mathematics), humans are, unequivocally, [animals](/Animal). We are, after all, multicellular, heterotrophic eukaryotes. Furthermore, while the word "[person](/Person)" is often used interchangeably with "human," this too opens a philosophical Pandora's Box. Extensive debate persists regarding whether [personhood](/Personhood) should be universally applied to all humans, or perhaps extended to all [sentient beings](/Sentient_being). Even more complex are the discussions surrounding whether a human can, under certain circumstances (such as entering a [persistent vegetative state](/Persistent_vegetative_state)), lose their personhood, and, perhaps most controversially, what precisely constitutes the [beginning of human personhood](/Beginning_of_human_personhood). Such discussions highlight our species' peculiar obsession with defining its own existence, even when the definitions are inherently slippery.

### Evolution

Our lineage, a branch on the vast tree of life, firmly places humans within the biological [family](/Family_(biology)) of [apes](/Ape) (specifically, the [superfamily Hominoidea](/Hominoidea)). The evolutionary path that eventually culminated in us, *Homo sapiens*, first diverged from [gibbons](/Gibbon) (the Hylobatidae family), then from [orangutans](/Orangutan) (genus *Pongo*), followed by [gorillas](/Gorilla) (genus *Gorilla*), and finally, from our closest living relatives, [chimpanzees](/Chimpanzee) and [bonobos](/Bonobo) (genus [Pan](/Pan_(genus))). This final, most significant split, separating the human lineage from that of chimpanzees and bonobos, occurred roughly 8 to 4 million years ago, deep within the late [Miocene](/Miocene) epoch. A particularly notable event during this divergence was the fusion of two ancestral chromosomes, resulting in humans possessing only 23 pairs of chromosomes, a distinct difference from the 24 pairs found in other apes. Following this crucial split from chimpanzees and bonobos, the early [hominins](/Hominini) underwent a period of significant diversification, branching into numerous species and at least two distinct genera. Of this rich tapestry of early human-like forms, all but one lineage – the genus [Homo](/Homo) and its sole surviving species, *[Homo sapiens](/Homo_sapiens)* – have since vanished into the fossil record.

The genus *Homo*, to which we belong, ultimately evolved from [Australopithecus](/Australopithecus). While the fossil record detailing this precise transition remains somewhat [scarce](/Human_fossils), the earliest documented members of *Homo* undeniably exhibit several key anatomical traits shared with their *Australopithecus* ancestors. Due to this frustratingly scant evidence, a definitive consensus on the exact timing of the divergence into the genus *Homo* continues to elude researchers. Some studies, employing sophisticated [molecular clock](/Molecular_clock) techniques, estimate the *Homo* genus made its appearance between 4.30 and 2.56 million years ago. However, other analyses, arguing that certain early *Homo* species might be incorrectly categorized, propose a more recent estimate, placing the genus's origin at approximately 1.87 million years ago. Such academic disagreements are, of course, entirely typical.

The earliest undisputed fossil evidence attributed to *Homo* is the 2.8 million-year-old specimen known as [LD 350-1](/LD_350-1), unearthed in [Ethiopia](/Ethiopia). The earliest formally named species within this genus are [Homo habilis](/Homo_habilis) and [Homo rudolfensis](/Homo_rudolfensis), both of which are believed to have evolved by 2.3 million years ago. A truly pivotal figure in our family tree, *[H. erectus](/Homo_erectus)* (whose African variant is sometimes designated *[H. ergaster](/Homo_ergaster)*), emerged around 2 million years ago. This species holds the distinction of being the first [archaic human](/Archaic_human) to venture beyond the African continent, successfully dispersing across the vast expanse of Eurasia. *H. erectus* also pioneered the development of the characteristically human [body plan](/Body_plan), setting the stage for future evolutionary refinements. Our direct ancestors, *[Homo sapiens](/Homo_sapiens)*, made their debut in Africa at least 300,000 years ago, evolving from a species frequently identified as either *[H. heidelbergensis](/Homo_heidelbergensis)* or *[H. rhodesiensis](/Homo_rhodesiensis)* – the descendants of *H. erectus* who remained within Africa. From their African homeland, *H. sapiens* embarked on their grand migration, systematically colonizing the globe, either gradually replacing or, more intriguingly, interbreeding with the existing local populations of archaic humans. This period of "[behavioral modernity](/Behavioral_modality)," marked by complex symbolic thought and innovative tool-making, became evident approximately 160,000 to 70,000 years ago, with some evidence suggesting it may have begun even earlier. This crucial developmental leap was likely a product of intense selective pressures, honed amidst the dramatic [natural climate change](/Climate_variability_and_change) events that characterized the [Middle](/Middle_Pleistocene) to [Late Pleistocene](/Late_Pleistocene) epochs in Africa.

The monumental "[out of Africa](/Recent_African_origin_of_modern_humans)" migration unfolded in at least two distinct waves. The first, a tentative probing, occurred around 130,000 to 100,000 years ago, while the second, more substantial dispersal, often referred to as the [Southern Dispersal](/Southern_Dispersal), commenced approximately 70,000 to 50,000 years ago. From there, *H. sapiens* proceeded with characteristic human thoroughness to colonize every continent and most major islands. They arrived in [Eurasia](/Eurasia) as early as 125,000 years ago, reached [Australia](/Australia) around 65,000 years ago, crossed into the [Americas](/The_Americas) roughly 15,000 years ago, and, in a testament to their seafaring prowess, colonized remote islands such as [Hawaii](/Hawaiian_Islands), [Easter Island](/Easter_Island), [Madagascar](/Madagascar), and [New Zealand](/New_Zealand) much more recently, between 300 and 1280 CE.

It's crucial to understand that human evolution was not a neat, linear progression, nor a simple branching tree. Instead, it was a far messier affair, involving significant [interbreeding between related species](/Interbreeding_between_archaic_and_modern_humans). Indeed, extensive [genomic research](/DNA) has revealed that hybridization between substantially diverged lineages was a surprisingly common occurrence throughout human evolution. [DNA](/DNA) evidence, rather inconveniently for those who prefer clean narratives, strongly suggests that several [genes](/Gene) of [Neanderthal](/Neanderthal) origin are present within virtually all non-sub-Saharan African populations. Furthermore, Neanderthals and other archaic hominins, such such as [Denisovans](/Denisovan), may have contributed a measurable portion – up to 6% – of their [genome](/Genome) to present-day non-sub-Saharan African humans. This means many of us carry echoes of these "extinct" relatives within our very cells.

Human evolution is marked by a series of profound [morphological](/Morphology_(biology)), [developmental](/Human_development_(biology)), [physiological](/Human_physiology), and [behavioral](/Human_behavior) transformations that have unfolded since the divergence from our [last common ancestor with chimpanzees](/Chimpanzee%E2%82%AChuman_last_common_ancestor). Among the most significant of these adaptations are our peculiar [hairlessness](/Prehistory_of_nakedness_and_clothing), our commitment to obligate bipedalism (standing upright, for all the world to see), a remarkable increase in [brain size](/Human_brain), and a notable decrease in [sexual dimorphism](/Sexual_dimorphism) compared to our ape cousins (a process known as [neoteny](/Neoteny)). The precise interplay and causal relationships between all these changes remain, as ever, the subject of ongoing and often heated scientific debate.

