### History

Ah, human history. A long, convoluted narrative, mostly of ourselves.

#### Prehistory

For an astonishingly long stretch of time – until approximately 12,000 years ago – all humans lived as [hunter-gatherers](/Hunter-gatherer). It was a lifestyle dictated by immediate needs, a constant dance with nature. Then, the [Neolithic Revolution](/Neolithic_Revolution), a transformative period marked by the invention of [agriculture](/Agriculture), began to unfold. This monumental shift first [took place](/Origins_of_agriculture_in_West_Asia) in [Southwest Asia](/Southwest_Asia), gradually spreading across vast sections of the [Old World](/Old_World) over many subsequent millennia. Not to be outdone, agriculture also emerged independently in other distant locales, including [Mesoamerica](/Mesoamerica) (around 6,000 years ago), various regions of China, [Papua New Guinea](/Papua_New_Guinea), and the [Sahel](/Sahel) and [West Savanna](/Sudanian_savanna) areas of Africa.

The consequences of this agricultural revolution were profound and irreversible. The establishment of permanent [human settlements](/Human_settlement), the strategic [domestication](/Domestication) of animals, and the innovative [use of metal tools](/Chalcolithic) collectively ushered in an unprecedented era of consistent food surplus – a luxury unknown for the entirety of human existence prior. This newfound abundance and sedentary lifestyle inevitably paved the way for the emergence of what we now refer to as early [civilizations](/Civilization). And so, the path to complex, stratified societies was set.

#### Ancient

The 4th millennium BCE witnessed a pivotal "[urban revolution](/Urban_revolution)" with the rise of complex [city-states](/City-state), particularly the sophisticated [Sumerian](/Sumer) cities nestled within [Mesopotamia](/Mesopotamia). It was within the bustling confines of these proto-cities that the earliest known form of writing, the intricate [cuneiform script](/Cuneiform_script), first emerged around 3000 BCE – a testament to the growing complexity of human record-keeping. Concurrent with these developments, other major [civilizations](/Civilization) began to flourish, notably [Ancient Egypt](/Ancient_Egypt) along the Nile and the enigmatic [Indus Valley Civilisation](/Indus_Valley_Civilisation). These burgeoning societies eventually engaged in intricate trade networks, exchanging goods and, more importantly, ideas. They innovated technologies that would fundamentally reshape human existence: the wheel, the plow, and the sail. Across the oceans, emerging by 3000 BCE, the [Caral–Supe civilization](/Caral%E2%80%93Supe_civilization) established itself as the oldest complex civilization in the Americas, proving that ingenuity was not confined to a single continent. During this era, humans also made significant strides in [astronomy](/Astronomy) and [mathematics](/Mathematics), culminating in monumental feats of engineering such as the construction of the [Great Pyramid of Giza](/Great_Pyramid_of_Giza). However, even these early achievements were not immune to the whims of nature; evidence points to a [severe drought](/4.2-kiloyear_event) lasting approximately a century, which may have contributed to the decline of several of these foundational civilizations, only for new ones to rise in their wake. The [Babylonians](/Babylonia) eventually asserted dominance over Mesopotamia, while other distinct cultures, such as the [Poverty Point culture](/Poverty_Point_culture) in North America, the [Minoans](/Minoan_civilization) in the Aegean, and the [Shang dynasty](/Shang_dynasty) in China, ascended to prominence in new geographical spheres. The [Late Bronze Age collapse](/Late_Bronze_Age_collapse), a period of widespread societal upheaval around 1200 BCE, led to the abrupt disappearance of numerous civilizations and marked the beginning of the [Greek Dark Ages](/Greek_Dark_Ages). During this turbulent transition, iron, a harder and more abundant metal, gradually superseded bronze, heralding the advent of the [Iron Age](/Iron_Age).

By the 5th century BCE, the systematic [recording of history](/Historiography) began to emerge as a recognized discipline, offering a significantly clearer, if still biased, window into the daily lives and political machinations of the time. Between the 8th and 6th centuries BCE, Europe entered the profound era of [classical antiquity](/Classical_antiquity), a period when the intellectual and cultural achievements of [ancient Greece](/Ancient_Greece) and [ancient Rome](/Ancient_Rome) reached their zenith, laying many of the foundations for later Western thought. Simultaneously, other powerful civilizations were rising across the globe. The [Maya civilization](/Maya_civilization) in Mesoamerica embarked on ambitious city-building projects and developed incredibly [complex calendars](/Maya_calendar), demonstrating a sophisticated understanding of celestial cycles. In Africa, the formidable [Kingdom of Aksum](/Kingdom_of_Aksum) supplanted the waning [Kingdom of Kush](/Kingdom_of_Kush), becoming a crucial nexus for trade between India and the Mediterranean world. In West Asia, the [Achaemenid Empire](/Achaemenid_Empire)'s pioneering system of centralized governance served as a blueprint for countless subsequent empires. Meanwhile, the [Gupta Empire](/Gupta_Empire) in India and the [Han dynasty](/Han_dynasty) in China are widely regarded as [golden ages](/Golden_ages) within their respective regions, periods of unparalleled advancement and cultural flourishing.

#### Post-classical

Following the rather dramatic [fall of the Western Roman Empire](/Fall_of_the_Western_Roman_Empire) in 476 CE – a collapse that, in hindsight, was perhaps inevitable – Europe plunged into the era known as the [Middle Ages](/Middle_Ages). During this period, [Christianity](/Christianity) and the omnipresent [Church](/Catholic_Church) became the undisputed founts of authority and education, shaping nearly every aspect of life. Meanwhile, in the Middle East, [Islam](/Islam) rose to become the dominant religion, rapidly expanding its influence across North Africa and beyond. This expansion ushered in an extraordinary [Islamic Golden Age](/Islamic_Golden_Age), a period of intellectual and artistic brilliance that inspired remarkable achievements in [architecture](/Architecture), saw the revival and reinterpretation of ancient scientific and technological advances, and cultivated a distinct, sophisticated way of life that, frankly, put much of contemporary Europe to shame. Predictably, the [Christian](/Christendom) and [Islamic worlds](/Islamic_world) would eventually collide, most notably in a series of brutal [holy wars](/Crusades) – with the [Kingdom of England](/Kingdom_of_England), the [Kingdom of France](/Kingdom_of_France), and the [Holy Roman Empire](/Holy_Roman_Empire) leading crusades in an attempt to seize control of the [Holy Land](/Holy_Land) from [Muslims](/Muslim).

Across the Atlantic, in the Americas, the period between 200 and 900 CE marked the [Classic Period](/Mesoamerican_Classic_period) in [Mesoamerica](/Mesoamerica), a time of flourishing urban centers and cultural sophistication. Further north, complex [Mississippian societies](/Mississippian_culture) began to emerge around 800 CE, showcasing intricate social and ceremonial structures. On the other side of the world, the formidable [Mongol Empire](/Mongol_Empire), under its relentless leaders, swept across and conquered much of [Eurasia](/Eurasia) throughout the 13th and 14th centuries, leaving an indelible mark on global history. During this same tumultuous period, the [Mali Empire](/Mali_Empire) in Africa expanded to become the continent's largest, stretching from [Senegambia](/Senegambia) to the [Ivory Coast](/Ivory_Coast), a testament to its organizational and military prowess. In Oceania, the [Tuʻi Tonga Empire](/Tu%CA%BBi_Tonga_Empire) rose to power, extending its influence across numerous islands in the South Pacific. By the late 15th century, the [Aztecs](/Aztecs) had established themselves as the dominant force in Mesoamerica, while the [Inca](/Inca) reigned supreme in the [Andes](/Andean_civilizations), each creating vast, intricate empires just before the arrival of outside forces.

#### Modern

The [early modern period](/Early_modern_period) in Europe and the Near East (roughly 1450–1800) commenced with the [final defeat of the Byzantine Empire](/Fall_of_Constantinople) and the subsequent, inevitable [rise of the Ottoman Empire](/Ottoman_Empire), which reshaped geopolitical power in the region. Meanwhile, Japan entered its culturally distinct [Edo period](/Edo_period), the powerful [Qing dynasty](/Qing_dynasty) ascended to rule in China, and the magnificent [Mughal Empire](/Mughal_Empire) held sway over much of India. Europe, following its "dark ages," experienced the vibrant intellectual and artistic explosion known as the [Renaissance](/Renaissance), beginning in the 15th century. This period soon transitioned into the [Age of Discovery](/Age_of_Discovery), an era defined by relentless exploration and the subsequent, often brutal, [colonizing](/Colonialism) of newly encountered regions. This expansion infamously included the [colonization of the Americas](/European_colonization_of_the_Americas), leading to the vast ecological and cultural exchange known as the [Columbian Exchange](/Columbian_Exchange). However, this era also brought with it the horrific [Atlantic slave trade](/Atlantic_slave_trade) and the tragic [genocide of the Americas' indigenous peoples](/Genocide_of_indigenous_people_in_the_Americas), dark stains on the ledger of human ambition. This period also heralded the [Scientific Revolution](/Scientific_Revolution), a time of unprecedented intellectual ferment and groundbreaking advances in [mathematics](/Mathematics), [mechanics](/Mechanics), [astronomy](/Astronomy), and [physiology](/Physiology), fundamentally altering humanity's understanding of the natural world.

The [late modern period](/Late_modern_period) (1800–present) then saw the profound and accelerating impact of the [Industrial](/Industrial_Revolution) and [Technological Revolution](/Technological_Revolution). This era brought forth a torrent of discoveries, from sophisticated [imaging technology](/Imaging_technology) to revolutionary innovations in transport and [energy development](/Energy_development), irrevocably altering the fabric of daily life. Influenced by the ideals of the [Enlightenment](/Age_of_Enlightenment), the Americas and Europe were convulsed by a period of profound political upheaval, collectively known as the [Age of Revolution](/Age_of_Revolution). The [Napoleonic Wars](/Napoleonic_Wars) tore through Europe in the early 1800s, leaving a trail of destruction and redrawing national borders. Spain, once a dominant colonial power, lost most of its vast holdings in the [New World](/New_World), while European powers continued their relentless [expansion into Africa](/Scramble_for_Africa) – where their control skyrocketed from a mere 10% to almost 90% in less than 50 years – and into Oceania. By the 19th century, the [British Empire](/British_Empire) had swelled to become the [world's largest empire](/List_of_largest_empires), its influence spanning the globe.

However, this tenuous [balance of power](/Balance_of_power_(international_relations)) among European nations proved inherently unstable, collapsing spectacularly in 1914 with the catastrophic outbreak of the [First World War](/World_War_I), a conflict that quickly became one of the deadliest in recorded history. The 1930s then ushered in [a worldwide economic crisis](/Great_Depression), a period of profound instability that, predictably, facilitated the rise of ruthless [authoritarian](/Authoritarian) regimes and culminated in the even more devastating [Second World War](/World_War_II), a global conflagration involving [almost all of the world's countries](/World_War_II_by_country). The sheer scale of destruction wrought by this war led to the inevitable collapse of most global empires, sparking widespread decolonization movements across the world.

Following the formal conclusion of the Second World War in 1945, a new geopolitical order emerged, dominated by two colossal powers: the [United States](/United_States) and the [Soviet Union](/Soviet_Union), who quickly established themselves as the remaining [global superpowers](/Global_superpower). This uneasy bipolarity immediately ignited the [Cold War](/Cold_War), a protracted struggle for global influence that played out through proxy conflicts, ideological battles, a terrifying [nuclear arms race](/Nuclear_arms_race), and even a competitive [space race](/Space_Race), before finally concluding with the collapse of the Soviet Union. The current era, often dubbed the [Information Age](/Information_Age), is characterized by the explosive development of the [Internet](/Internet) and increasingly sophisticated [artificial intelligence](/Artificial_intelligence) systems. It sees the world becoming ever more profoundly [globalized](/Globalization) and intricately interconnected, for better or worse.

### Habitat and population

Early human settlements, quite logically, were entirely dependent on proximity to reliable [water resources](/Water_resources) and – depending on the prevailing lifestyle – other essential [natural resources](/Natural_resource) vital for [subsistence](/Subsistence). This included, for instance, robust populations of animal prey for [hunting](/Hunting) and fertile [arable land](/Arable_land) suitable for cultivating crops and grazing livestock. Modern humans, however, have developed an almost unparalleled capacity for fundamentally altering their [habitats](/Habitat_(ecology)) through the relentless application of [technology](/Technology), elaborate [irrigation](/Irrigation) systems, ambitious [urban planning](/Urban_planning), massive construction projects, widespread [deforestation](/Deforestation), and the often-unintended consequence of [desertification](/Desertification). Despite our supposed mastery over nature, [human settlements](/Human_settlement) remain stubbornly [vulnerable](/Vulnerability) to the destructive forces of [natural disasters](/Natural_disasters), particularly those unwisely situated in hazardous locations or constructed with a lamentable lack of quality. The pervasive human tendency for grouping and deliberate habitat alteration is almost always driven by a set of predictable goals: the desire for enhanced protection, the accumulation of comforts or material wealth, the expansion of available food sources, the pursuit of [aesthetics](/Aesthetics), the relentless increase of [knowledge](/Knowledge), or the optimization of resource exchange.

Humans, despite possessing a surprisingly low or narrow biological tolerance for many of Earth's truly extreme environments, are nonetheless one of the most [adaptable](/Adaptation) species. Currently, our species maintains a presence in all eight recognized [biogeographical realms](/Biogeographical_realms). However, our foothold in the [Antarctic realm](/Antarctic_realm) remains severely limited, primarily confined to isolated [research stations](/Research_stations_in_Antarctica), with a noticeable annual population decline during the harsh winter months. Elsewhere, humans have, with characteristic fervor, established [nation-states](/Nation_state) across the other seven realms, including diverse countries such as [South Africa](/South_Africa), [India](/India), [Russia](/Russia), [Australia](/Australia), [Fiji](/Fiji), the [United States](/United_States), and [Brazil](/Brazil), each nestled within a distinct biogeographical domain.

Within the relatively brief span of the last century, humans have pushed the boundaries of exploration further, venturing into the abyssal [deep sea](/Deep_sea) and the boundless expanse of [outer space](/Outer_space). Sustained human habitation within these profoundly hostile environments is both prohibitively restrictive and astronomically expensive, typically limited in duration and confined to highly specialized [scientific](/Scientific), [military](/Military), or [industrial](/Industry_(economics)) expeditions. Yet, with a mix of scientific ambition and raw determination, humans [have visited](/Exploration_of_the_Moon) the [Moon](/Moon) itself and, through the deployment of human-made [robotic spacecraft](/Robotic_spacecraft), have made our presence known on other distant [celestial bodies](/Celestial_bodies). Since the year 2000, humanity has maintained a continuous presence [in space](/Human_presence_in_space) through the ongoing habitation of the [International Space Station](/International_Space_Station) – a testament to our stubborn refusal to stay put.

Through the ingenious application of advanced tools and sophisticated [clothing](/Clothing), humans have managed to dramatically extend their physiological tolerance to an astonishingly wide spectrum of temperatures, [humidities](/Humidity), and altitudes. As a direct consequence, humans are now a truly [cosmopolitan](/Cosmopolitan_distribution) species, found in virtually every region of the world. We inhabit everything from dense [tropical rainforests](/Tropical_rainforest) to parched [arid deserts](/Desert), from the brutally cold [arctic regions](/Arctic_region) to the densely packed, often heavily polluted urban sprawl of our cities. This stands in stark contrast to most other species, whose geographical distribution is severely restricted by their limited adaptability. The [human population](/Human_population), however, is far from uniformly distributed across the [Earth](/Earth)'s surface. Population density varies wildly from one region to another, with vast stretches of the planet remaining almost completely uninhabited, such as the frozen expanse of [Antarctica](/Antarctica) and the immense, silent depths of the ocean. The majority of humans (a staggering 61%) reside in Asia; the remainder are distributed across the Americas (14%), Africa (14%), Europe (11%), and Oceania (a mere 0.5%).

A rather sobering statistic: humans and their extensively [domesticated animals](/Domestication) now account for a staggering 96% of all mammalian [biomass](/Biomass_(ecology)) on Earth. All wild mammals, by comparison, represent a paltry 4%. This stark imbalance speaks volumes about our species' dominance – and its ecological footprint.

Estimates regarding the global human population at the dawn of agriculture, around 10,000 BCE, vary widely, ranging from a modest 1 million to a more substantial 15 million individuals. By the 4th century AD, it's believed that approximately 50–60 million people inhabited the combined eastern and western [Roman Empire](/Roman_Empire). However, the course of human population history has been anything but smooth. Devastating [bubonic plagues](/Bubonic_plague), first documented in the 6th century AD, dramatically reduced populations, with the infamous [Black Death](/Black_Death) alone claiming the lives of an estimated 75–200 million people across [Eurasia](/Eurasia) and [North Africa](/North_Africa). Despite such catastrophic setbacks, the human population eventually rebounded and accelerated. It is believed to have reached one [billion](/Billion) around 1800, then embarked on an exponential surge, hitting two billion by 1930, three billion by 1960, four by 1975, five by 1987, and six billion by 1999. It surpassed seven billion in 2011 and, with relentless momentum, passed eight billion in November 2022. To put this into perspective, it took over two million years of [human prehistory](/Prehistory) and [history](/Human_history) for the global population to reach one billion, yet only a mere 207 years more to multiply to seven billion. The combined [biomass](/Biomass_(ecology)) of the carbon contained within all humans on Earth in 2018 was estimated at 60 million tons, a mass approximately 10 times greater than that of all non-domesticated mammals combined.

In 2018, a significant demographic milestone was reached: 4.2 billion humans (55% of the global total) resided in urban areas, a dramatic increase from just 751 million in 1950. The most heavily urbanized regions include Northern America (82%), Latin America (81%), Europe (74%), and Oceania (68%). Conversely, Africa and Asia continue to host nearly 90% of the world's 3.4 billion rural population. While cities offer undeniable advantages, they also present a myriad of problems for their human inhabitants, including various forms of [pollution](/Pollution) and pervasive [crime](/Crime), particularly concentrated in inner-city and suburban [slums](/Slum). A testament, perhaps, to our inability to perfectly manage our own creations.

### Biology

Let's delve into the mechanics of this species, shall we?

#### Anatomy and physiology

Most aspects of human [physiology](/Physiology) are, rather unsurprisingly, closely [homologous](/Homology_(biology)) to corresponding aspects of animal physiology. Our [dental formula](/Dental_formula) is 2.1.2.32.1.2.3, a pattern shared with other [catarrhines](/Catarrhini). However, humans possess proportionately shorter [palates](/Palate) and significantly smaller [teeth](/Human_tooth) than other primates. We are, in fact, the only primates to exhibit short, relatively flush [canine teeth](/Canine_teeth), a feature that, if you think about it, somewhat undermines our claim to being fearsome predators. Our teeth also have a characteristic tendency to be crowded, with gaps from lost teeth usually closing up rather quickly in younger individuals. A curious evolutionary trend sees humans gradually losing their [third molars](/Wisdom_teeth) (wisdom teeth), with some individuals even being born congenitally without them – perhaps a sign of future dental simplicity, or just another minor inconvenience.

Humans, like chimpanzees, still carry the echo of a [vestigial](/Vestigiality) tail – a coccyx, hidden from view, a silent reminder of our distant past. We also share an [appendix](/Appendix_(anatomy)) (another delightful vestige), flexible shoulder joints, grasping fingers, and, crucially, [opposable thumbs](/Opposable_thumb) – the latter being a key ingredient in our tool-making prowess. Our chest, in contrast to the funnel shape common in other apes, is more barrel-shaped, an adaptation directly linked to our bipedal respiration. Beyond the obvious distinctions of bipedalism and brain size, humans primarily differ from chimpanzees in their senses of [smelling](/Smelling) and [hearing](/Hearing), and in their methods of [digesting proteins](/Digestion). While we possess a density of [hair follicles](/Hair_follicle) comparable to other apes, the vast majority of it is [vellus hair](/Vellus_hair) – so short and wispy as to be virtually invisible. This near-nakedness is compensated by an abundance of approximately 2 million [sweat glands](/Sweat_gland) distributed across our entire bodies, a stark contrast to chimpanzees, whose sweat glands are sparse and mainly concentrated on their palms and soles. This adaptation, it seems, helps us cool off after a particularly strenuous intellectual endeavor, or perhaps just a brisk walk.

It's estimated that the global average [height for an adult human](/Human_height) male hovers around 171 cm (5 ft 7 in), while adult females average about 159 cm (5 ft 3 in). A rather predictable shrinkage of stature may commence in middle age for some, but it tends to become a typical, if somewhat disheartening, characteristic in the extremely [aged](/Old_age). Throughout recorded history, human populations have, on a broad scale, consistently increased in height, a phenomenon likely attributable to improved nutrition, better healthcare, and generally enhanced living conditions. The average [mass](/Body_weight) of an adult human is approximately 59 kg (130 lb) for females and 77 kg (170 lb) for males. Like many other physiological conditions, body weight and body type are influenced by a complex interplay of [genetic susceptibility](/Genetic_predisposition) and environmental factors, leading to considerable variation among individuals.

Humans possess a significantly faster and more accurate [throw](/Throw) than virtually any other animal – a skill that was undoubtedly crucial for hunting and, let's be honest, for throwing things at each other. We are also among the most accomplished long-distance runners in the animal kingdom, though, ironically, we are often outpaced over short bursts. Our thinner body hair and more efficient sweat glands are key physiological adaptations that help us avoid [heat exhaustion](/Heat_exhaustion) during prolonged periods of running. Compared to other apes, the human [heart](/Heart) exhibits a greater [stroke volume](/Stroke_volume) and [cardiac output](/Cardiac_output), and our [aorta](/Aorta) is proportionately larger – perhaps a necessary upgrade for powering our large, demanding brains.

#### Genetics

Humans are, much like the majority of [animals](/Animal), [plants](/Plant), and [fungi](/Fungus), a [eukaryotic](/Eukaryote) species, and, like most animals, we are [diploid](/Ploidy). Each [somatic cell](/Somatic_cell) within our bodies contains two complete sets of 23 [chromosomes](/Chromosome), with each set meticulously inherited from one parent. Our [gametes](/Gamete), however, possess only a single set of chromosomes, a carefully shuffled mixture of the two parental sets. Among these 23 pairs of chromosomes, 22 are [autosomes](/Autosome), and one crucial pair consists of the [sex chromosomes](/Sex-determination_system). Following the typical mammalian [XY sex-determination system](/XY_sex-determination_system), females possess two X chromosomes (XX), while males carry one X and one Y chromosome (XY). The complex interplay of [genes](/Gene) and the [environment](/Environment_(biophysical)) profoundly influences human biological variation, manifesting in everything from visible characteristics and [physiology](/Physiology) to disease susceptibility and mental abilities. The precise extent of influence exerted by [genes and environment](/Environment_(biophysical)) on specific traits remains, as ever, a subject of ongoing scientific inquiry.

While it is a well-established fact that no two humans – not even [monozygotic twins](/Monozygotic_twins) – are truly genetically identical, the average genetic similarity between any two randomly selected humans ranges from 99.5% to 99.9%. This makes our species remarkably [homogeneous](/Human_genetic_variation) when compared to other great apes, including our chimpanzee cousins. This surprisingly small degree of genetic variation in human [DNA](/DNA), relative to many other species, strongly suggests a significant [population bottleneck](/Population_bottleneck) occurred during the [Late Pleistocene](/Late_Pleistocene) epoch (approximately 100,000 years ago), a period when the entire human population was drastically reduced to a relatively small number of breeding pairs. Despite this ancient bottleneck, the relentless forces of [natural selection](/Natural_selection) have continued to exert their influence on human populations, with clear evidence indicating that certain regions of the [genome](/Genome) have undergone [directional selection](/Directional_selection) within the last 15,000 years.

The complete [human genome](/Human_genome) was first painstakingly sequenced in 2001, a monumental scientific achievement. By 2020, hundreds of thousands of individual human genomes had been sequenced, painting an increasingly detailed picture of our genetic landscape. In 2012, the ambitious [International HapMap Project](/International_HapMap_Project) had already compared the genomes of 1,184 individuals drawn from 11 diverse populations, identifying a staggering 1.6 million [single nucleotide polymorphisms](/Single_nucleotide_polymorphisms) (SNPs). African populations, as expected given our species' origin, harbor the highest number of unique genetic variants. While many common variants found in non-African populations are also present on the African continent, a significant number of private variants are found exclusively in other regions, particularly [Oceania](/Oceania) and [the Americas](/The_Americas). As of 2010, estimates suggest that humans possess approximately 22,000 [genes](/Gene). By analyzing [mitochondrial DNA](/MtDNA), which is inherited exclusively from the mother, geneticists have concluded that the last female common ancestor whose [genetic marker](/Genetic_marker) is present in all modern humans, a figure famously dubbed [mitochondrial Eve](/Mitochondrial_Eve), must have lived roughly 90,000 to 200,000 years ago.

#### Life cycle

The primary mode of [human reproduction](/Human_reproduction) involves [internal fertilization](/Internal_fertilization) through [sexual intercourse](/Human_sexual_intercourse), though modern advances in [assisted reproductive technology](/Assisted_reproductive_technology) procedures offer alternative pathways. The average [gestation](/Gestation) period for a human pregnancy is approximately 38 weeks, although a normal, healthy pregnancy can naturally vary by as much as 37 days. [Embryonic development](/Human_embryo) in humans encompasses the first eight weeks; from the beginning of the ninth week until birth, the developing organism is referred to as a [fetus](/Fetus). For medical reasons, humans have developed the capacity to [induce early labor](/Labor_induction) or perform a [caesarean section](/Caesarean_section) when necessary. In developed countries, [infants](/Infant) typically weigh between 3–4 kg (7–9 lb) and measure 47–53 cm (19–21 in) in height at birth. However, [low birth weight](/Low_birth_weight) remains a prevalent and concerning issue in developing countries, tragically contributing to the high rates of [infant mortality](/Infant_mortality) in these regions.

Compared with other species, human [childbirth](/Childbirth) is notoriously dangerous, carrying a significantly higher risk of complications and even death. The size of the fetal head is, rather inconveniently, much more closely matched to the dimensions of the [pelvis](/Pelvis) than in other primates. The precise evolutionary reasons for this tight fit are not yet fully understood, but it undeniably contributes to a painful and often protracted labor that can easily extend for 24 hours or even longer. Thankfully, the chances of a successful labor increased dramatically during the 20th century in wealthier nations, largely due to the advent of new medical technologies and interventions. In stark contrast, pregnancy and [natural childbirth](/Natural_childbirth) continue to be hazardous ordeals in many developing regions of the world, where [maternal death rates](/Maternal_death_rates) are tragically approximately 100 times greater than in developed countries.

Uniquely among primates, both the mother and the father often actively participate in the care of human offspring, a stark contrast to other primate species where parental care is predominantly, if not exclusively, provided by the mother. Born utterly [helpless at birth](/Altricial), humans undergo an extended period of growth and development, typically reaching [sexual maturity](/Sexual_maturity) between 15 and 17 years of age. The human [life span](/Life_expectancy) is broadly divided into various stages, typically ranging from three to twelve distinct phases. Common classifications include [infancy](/Infant), [childhood](/Childhood), [adolescence](/Adolescence), [adulthood](/Adult), and [old age](/Old_age). The precise duration of these stages has fluctuated across different cultures and historical periods, but it is characterized by an unusually rapid growth spurt during adolescence. Human females undergo [menopause](/Menopause), a biological transition that renders them [infertile](/Infertility) around the age of 50. It has been proposed that menopause, rather than being a reproductive endpoint, actually enhances a woman's overall reproductive success by allowing her to redirect more time and resources towards her existing offspring and, crucially, their children – a concept known as the [grandmother hypothesis](/Grandmother_hypothesis).

The ultimate [life span](/Life_span) of an individual human is determined by two primary factors: their genetic endowment and the cumulative impact of their lifestyle choices. For a multitude of reasons, including underlying biological and genetic predispositions, women, on average, tend to live approximately four years longer than men. As of 2018, the global average [life expectancy at birth](/Life_expectancy_at_birth) for a girl was estimated to be 74.9 years, compared to 70.4 years for a boy. However, significant geographical disparities in human life expectancy persist, largely correlating with levels of economic development. For instance, life expectancy at birth in [Hong Kong](/Hong_Kong) stands at an impressive 87.6 years for girls and 81.8 years for boys, while in the [Central African Republic](/Central_African_Republic), these figures tragically plummet to 55.0 years for girls and a mere 50.6 years for boys. The developed world is currently experiencing a demographic shift, characterized by an aging population, with the median age hovering around 40 years. In contrast, the [developing world](/Third_world) maintains a significantly younger median age, typically between 15 and 20 years. This disparity is stark: while one in five Europeans is 60 years of age or older, only one in twenty Africans falls into this age bracket. In 2012, the [United Nations](/United_Nations) estimated that there were approximately 316,600 living [centenarians](/Centenarians) (humans aged 100 or older) worldwide – a testament to both medical advancements and sheer stubbornness.

